China's household debt rate is closer to that of the United States than can not afford to buy a home is more terrible is not to pay the debt ?
Recently , everyone is talking about the recent changes in the real estate policy , is the real estate policy to be loosened again ? The land policy supply main body diversification , will let the house price decline ?
But when we were worried about real estate prices , about macro-economic regulation , and about the future of the real estate market , the People's Daily wrote again . Last time we talked specifically about the adjustment of real estate regulation in the People's Daily , and now the People's Daily is writing about a more serious topic than buying affordable housing . Is that even if you can afford to buy a house , you can afford to pay the debt ?
Today , let's talk about a more serious problem than buying a house : loan repayment .
1 . China's growing housing debt crisis
In November 2017 , the National Finance and Development Laboratory of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and the National Balance Sheet Research Center issued a report on the process of deleveraging in China in the third quarter , pointing out that the rate of leverage in the residential sector continued to rise from 47.4 percent in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.3 percent in the third quarter , up from 48.3 percent in the second quarter of 2017 to 3.8 percent in the third quarter of 2017 .
The debt ratio of the resident sector in the whole real economy has increased , and the leverage rate has risen faster .
Studies show that Chinese households' liabilities in financial institutions are dominated by consumer loans , accounting for about two-thirds of residents' liabilities , about twice as much as operating loans .
Among them , in consumer loans , housing loans mainly accounted for about 80 % of the medium-and long-term loans , but from an incremental point of view , short-term consumer loans grew faster , higher than medium-and long-term loans .
In addition , China's household debt rate only counts the total amount of credit received by the family sector from financial institutions , while Chinese households still have a lot of private loans , including borrowing money from relatives and friends , with large-scale implicit debt .
According to statistics from the Su Ning Institute of Finance , the leverage rate for Chinese residents was only 3 % in 1996 and 18 % in 2008 , but it has started to grow rapidly since 2008 , doubling to 36.4 % in just six years and reaching 48.6 % in the third quarter of 2017 .
Last May , HSBC released a survey of nearly tens of thousands of people across nine countries .
The report is aimed at " millennium " young people from nine countries ( born between 1980 and 2000 ) .
China's housing ownership rate for young people after 80 and 90 is as high as 70 % , far ahead of Mexico ( 46 % ) and twice the level of the US target ( 35 % ) , the report said .
The figures tell us that one of the most likely problems is that the biggest potential " grey rhinoceros " for Chinese residents at this stage is likely to be out of debt compared to not being able to afford a home .
Second , why the housing debt crisis is the most serious problem ?
As we have analyzed before , although we have been saying that Chinese house prices are relatively high , but compared to other countries in the world , China's housing ownership rate is actually quite high , so not so high house prices can not afford to buy a house , I am afraid that many friends now have to ask the question is that you can still afford a loan ?
As we look at the real estate market around the world , China's real estate market , due to its late start , has not seen a major real estate crisis in addition to what we said earlier in Hainan , but just a decade ago the origin of the global financial tsunami in 2008 was the real estate crisis in the United States .
The cause of the housing crisis in the United States was blamed on Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac : Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac .
At that time , in the golden age of the United States , real estate companies sold their homes to low-income people at a very low price in order to expand sales . At a time when the U . S . economy was doing well , the real estate market was booming , but not for a long time , as the U . S . economy stagnated , resulting in a decline in the income of home buyers , a large number of household spending began to decline .
However , the current state of the United States was an integral part of American household assets , financial assets and real estate assets . Almost all of the family assets of low-income groups in the United States were real estate , while most of the top 20 % of the high-income groups were financial assets , resulting in a higher debt ratio of real estate in the poorer households in the United States .
A serious fact is that these people buy their homes when the economy is better , so the amount of money they pay for their mortgages is also calculated on the basis of their better income . When incomes fall , the pressure on mortgage loans not only does not decrease , but even because some subprime schemes have become more volatile , so the real estate problems of these American families have gradually evolved into a real estate crisis .
As a result , some people cannot afford to pay their mortgages because their incomes are too low , so the banks begin to take back their homes , and when the banks take back their properties from delinquent homeowners , they sell them at very low prices , leading to a gradual decline in house prices in the region , creating a vicious circle in which more and more homeowners find their homes worth even less than their own loans .
A great vicious circle was thus formed :
" The economy is bad--incomes are falling--some people can't afford a mortgage--banks are selling their homes at low prices--house prices are falling--more people stop paying their mortgages--banks are selling them--and house prices are falling . . . "
The problem is more than that , because house prices continue to fall , people stop paying the house to the bank and you don't have any debt . If the bank auctions the house and you don't get the money you owe the bank , then you still need to pay back the money . Simply put , if you use the first 600,000 , 2.4 million loans to buy a 3 million-million-dollar house , and when the house goes down to 2 million , you don't have to pay the bank .
So , in one vicious cycle after another , the U . S . economy gradually collapsed , leading to the U . S . financial crisis of 2008 .
Therefore , at this stage , China's household debt rate reached a high of 46.8 % is a very need to be vigilant , this figure is still below the level of developed countries at present , but the beginning of the problem has begun to emerge , the country has repeatedly stressed the deleveraging problem since last year , this is a very prescient judgment , if the household debt rate is allowed to continue to rise , it will inevitably lead to huge financial risks , so it is necessary to prevent the emergence of financial risks .
So after the house is used to live , not to stir-fry the location , the state has accelerated the establishment of multi-agent supply , multi-channel security , rent-purchase and other multiple measures , further defuse potential risks .
For our individual family , we must give up the thinking of real estate speculation , buy a house according to our ability , to avoid their own family into a huge burden , only a reasonable assessment of their income and debt level is a healthy family wealth development road . 6 . Fortune knocks once at least at every man's gate , at every man's gate , at every man's gate , at every man's gate , and at every man's gate .
Authors : special researcher , financial columnist , financial commentator , Su Ning Institute of Finance .
First micro-letter public number : Jiang Hanvision observation ( jianghanview )
